</mei>

<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Non-diatonic substitutions: G major → C (V), A major → Dm (vi). This keeps all harp
  notes within F major scale. The melody notes G/A/D work over C and Dm respectively.
- Phrase 1 (mm. 1–4): I–V alternation; m.1 opens with quartal "44" (F-C) for open sound.
  m.3 uses full IV arp (Bb-D-F ascending and back). m.4 V7 provides forward pull.
- Phrase 2 (mm. 5–8): Fast harmonic rhythm (3 chords per bar in mm. 5–6) for "voices raising."
  m.8 I–V¹ 1st inversion for smoother bass motion (E2→C2 not F2→C2).
- Phrase 3 (mm. 9–12): High register RH (C5-F5 in m.10) — climax approach.
  m.11 I¹ 1st inversion for inner voice variety. m.12 vi pedal under melody's A descent.
- Phrase 4 (mm. 13–16): Sustained ii in m.13 (4-note LH, full weight). Chain ii7→V→I
  in mm. 15–16 provides strong cadential resolution.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Soprano (RH upper voice): Bb4→D5 | C5→F5 | C5→Bb4 | D5→Bb4 — arch contour.
- Bass walk mm. 14–15: A2→G2→F2 / G2→Bb2→C2 — smooth contrary motion with soprano.
- m.6 inner descent: RH Bb4→A4→G4 mirrors melody — parallel 6ths with bass.
- m.13 held ii chord: LH 4-note open voicing (G2-D3-G3-Bb3) — strongest LH in piece.

TEXTURE ARC:
- mm. 1–4: Light entry — quartal opening, 2-note RH, 3-note LH; I–IV–V motion
- mm. 5–8: Fast harmonic rhythm — 1 chord/beat in mm. 5–6, momentum builds
- mm. 9–12: High RH register — climax approach, 1st inversion variety
- mm. 13–16: Sustained ii pedal → step-by-step descent → full root-position I close
-->
